-1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 271 "3.  Fundamental Theorem of Alg
ebra.  The Fundamental Theorem of Algebra asserts that every non-const
ant polynomial (with complex-valued coefficients) has a root (a zero, \+
a solution).  A consequence of the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra is t
hat every polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 276 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 13 " has e
xactly " }{TEXT 277 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 108 " roots.  An alternate formula
tion of this consequence would be that every non-constant polynomial o
f degree " }{TEXT 279 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 38 " can be factored into a prod
uct of a  " }{TEXT 278 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 16 " linear factors." }}{PARA 
0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 35 "Consider the fo
