" 0 "" {TEXT -1 650 "In those cases where Maple did not find enough li
near factors, there is a reason why Maple did not.  Maple makes an ass
umption that if the coefficients of a polynomial are all given exactly
 (as integers or rational numbers [ratios of integer]), then you are o
nly interested in finding exact factors (factors where the coefficient
s are integers or rational numbers).  The Fundamental Theorem of Algeb
ra doesn't guarantee that the factors of  a polynomial will necessaril
y have the same kind of coefficients as the polynomial, only the polyn
omial can be factored.  You can force Maple to report additional (appr
oximate) factors.  For example,  compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!
\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(h,sqrt(5))
;" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"*$\"\"&#F&\"\"#F&F
&,&F%F&F'!\"\"F&,&F%F&F&F&F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}
{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 52 "What is the difference?  The extra-term i
s called a " }{TEXT 280 18 "field extension.  " }{TEXT -1 178 "Adding \+
it tells Maple to consider additonal factors where the coefficients ar
e allowed to include elements from the field extension.  It is fairly \+
clear from the factoriztion of " }{TEXT 281 1 "h" }{TEXT -1 280 " all \+
by itself that something involving  sqrt(5)  would have to be included
.  However, there are problems where there is not a obvious clue as to
 which specific field extension should be added.  If you are willing t
o accept an appropriate solution, then using the field extension " }
{TEXT 282 4 "real" }{TEXT -1 179 " tells Maple to factor the polynomia
l using a floating point approximation scheme.  For example, consider \+
(here I am pretending I don't see that adding  sqrt(5) would be optima
l):" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" 
{MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(h);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&%\"
xG\"\"\"F&F&F&,&*$)F%\"\"#F&F&\"\"&!\"\"F&" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "
" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(h,real);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#
*(,&%\"xG\"\"\"$\"+xz1OA!\"*F&F&,&F%F&$F&\"\"!F&F&,&F%F&$\"+xz1OAF)!\"
\"F&" }}}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 0 "" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 91 "
Finally, the Fundamental Theorem of Algebra does not guarantee that a \+
polynomial of degree " }{TEXT 283 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 11 " will have " }
{TEXT 284 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 53 " real linear factors.  Rather, only hat \+
it will have " }{TEXT 285 1 "n" }{TEXT -1 134 " linear factors.  What \+
is the difference?  Some of the factors may involve complex roots rath
er than real roots.  For example compare:" }}{PARA 0 "" 0 "" {TEXT -1 
0 "" }}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 10 "factor(F);" }}{PARA 
11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*&,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F)\"#7!\"\"F),&F%F)F*
F)F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 "> " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 18 "factor(F,sqrt(3));
" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 20 "6#*(,&*$)%\"xG\"\"#\"\"\"F)\"#7F)F),
&F'F)*&F(F)\"\"$#F)F(!\"\"F),&F'F)*&F(F)F-F.F)F)" }}}{EXCHG {PARA 0 ">
 " 0 "" {MPLTEXT 1 0 15 "factor(F,real);" }}{PARA 11 "" 1 "" {XPPMATH 
